ordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baggard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Magard</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Maghard</i>, from elements meaning ‘power’ + ‘hard, strong’. <i>Maggard</i> is on record as a surname in medieval Suffolk but is now rare or absent in Britain. See also   Madgett   and   Matchett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maggert","meanings":["English: variant of   Maggard  ."]},{"name":"Madge","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Magge</i>, a pet form of either <i>Margery</i> or <i>Margaret</i> (compare   Maggard   and see   Margeson  )."]},{"name":"Madgett","meanings":["English (Norfolk): perhaps a variant pronunciation of   Maggard  , from the Old French personal name <i>Magard</i>, <i>Machard</i>, with reduction of <i>-ard</i> to <i>-et</i>, or perhaps from <i>Maget</i> or <i>Machet</i> as Old French pet forms of the same name + the diminutive suffix <i>-et</i>.   Matchett   is probably another variant. Alternatively, <i>Madgett</i> is from a Middle English female personal name <i>Magget</i>, an unrecorded diminutive form of <i>Magge</i> (see   Madge  ), itself a pet form of either <i>Margery</i> or <i>Margaret</i>."]},{"name":"Maggart","meanings":["English: variant of   Maggard  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it 